#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:5
msgid "xdist: pytest distributed testing plugin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:7
msgid ""
"The `pytest-xdist`_ plugin extends ``pytest`` with some unique test "
"execution modes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:10
msgid ""
"Looponfail: run your tests repeatedly in a subprocess.  After each run, "
"``pytest`` waits until a file in your project changes and then re-runs the "
"previously failing tests.  This is repeated until all tests pass.  At this "
"point a full run is again performed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:15
msgid ""
"multiprocess Load-balancing: if you have multiple CPUs or hosts you can use "
"them for a combined test run.  This allows to speed up development or to use "
"special resources of remote machines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:19
msgid ""
"Multi-Platform coverage: you can specify different Python interpreters or "
"different platforms and run tests in parallel on all of them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:22
msgid ""
"Before running tests remotely, ``pytest`` efficiently \"rsyncs\" your "
"program source code to the remote place.  All test results are reported back "
"and displayed to your local terminal. You may specify different Python "
"versions and interpreters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:29
msgid "Installation of xdist plugin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:31
msgid "Install the plugin with::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:33
msgid ""
"easy_install pytest-xdist\n"
"\n"
"# or\n"
"\n"
"pip install pytest-xdist"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:39
msgid ""
"or use the package in develop/in-place mode with a checkout of the `pytest-"
"xdist repository`_ ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:42
msgid "python setup.py develop"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:46
msgid "Usage examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:51
msgid "Speed up test runs by sending tests to multiple CPUs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:53
msgid "To send tests to multiple CPUs, type::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:55
msgid "py.test -n NUM"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:57
msgid ""
"Especially for longer running tests or tests requiring a lot of I/O this can "
"lead to considerable speed ups."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:62
msgid "Running tests in a Python subprocess"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:64
msgid ""
"To instantiate a Python-2.7 subprocess and send tests to it, you may type::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:66
msgid "py.test -d --tx popen//python=python2.7"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:68
msgid ""
"This will start a subprocess which is run with the \"python2.7\" Python "
"interpreter, found in your system binary lookup path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:71
msgid "If you prefix the --tx option value like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:73
msgid "py.test -d --tx 3*popen//python=python2.7"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:75
msgid ""
"then three subprocesses would be created and the tests will be distributed "
"to three subprocesses and run simultanously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:82
msgid "Running tests in looponfailing mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:84
msgid ""
"For refactoring a project with a medium or large test suite you can use the "
"looponfailing mode. Simply add the ``--f`` option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:87
msgid "py.test -f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:89
msgid ""
"and ``pytest`` will run your tests. Assuming you have failures it will then "
"wait for file changes and re-run the failing test set.  File changes are "
"detected by looking at ``looponfailingroots`` root directories and all of "
"their contents (recursively).  If the default for this value does not work "
"for you you can change it in your project by setting a configuration option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:93
msgid ""
"# content of a pytest.ini, setup.cfg or tox.ini file\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"looponfailroots = mypkg testdir"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:97
msgid ""
"This would lead to only looking for file changes in the respective "
"directories, specified relatively to the ini-file's directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:100
msgid "Sending tests to remote SSH accounts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:102
msgid ""
"Suppose you have a package ``mypkg`` which contains some tests that you can "
"successfully run locally. And you also have a ssh-reachable machine "
"``myhost``.  Then you can ad-hoc distribute your tests by typing::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:107
msgid "py.test -d --tx ssh=myhostpopen --rsyncdir mypkg mypkg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:109
msgid ""
"This will synchronize your ``mypkg`` package directory with a remote ssh "
"account and then collect and run your tests at the remote side."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:113
msgid ""
"You can specify multiple ``--rsyncdir`` directories to be sent to the remote "
"side."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:127
msgid "Sending tests to remote Socket Servers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:129
msgid ""
"Download the single-module `socketserver.py`_ Python program and run it like "
"this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:132
msgid "python socketserver.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:134
msgid ""
"It will tell you that it starts listening on the default port.  You can now "
"on your home machine specify this new socket host with something like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:138
msgid "py.test -d --tx socket=192.168.1.102:8888 --rsyncdir mypkg mypkg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:144
msgid "Running tests on many platforms at once"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:146
msgid "The basic command to run tests on multiple platforms is::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:148
msgid "py.test --dist=each --tx=spec1 --tx=spec2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:150
msgid ""
"If you specify a windows host, an OSX host and a Linux environment this "
"command will send each tests to all platforms - and report back failures "
"from all platforms at once.   The specifications strings use the `xspec "
"syntax`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:162
msgid "Specifying test exec environments in an ini file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:164
msgid ""
"pytest (since version 2.0) supports ini-style configuration. For example, "
"you could make running with three subprocesses your default::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:167
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = -n3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:170
msgid "You can also add default environments like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:172
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = --tx ssh=myhost//python=python2.7 --tx ssh=myhost//python=python2.6"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:175
msgid "and then just type::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:177
msgid "py.test --dist=each"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:179
msgid "to run tests in each of the environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:182
msgid "Specifying \"rsync\" dirs in an ini-file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:184
msgid ""
"In a ``tox.ini`` or ``setup.cfg`` file in your root project directory you "
"may specify directories to include or to exclude in synchronisation::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:187
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"rsyncdirs = . mypkg helperpkg\n"
"rsyncignore = .hg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/xdist.rst:191
msgid ""
"These directory specifications are relative to the directory where the "
"configuration file was found."
msgstr ""
